Key Match Events: Adama Malouda Traoré had another chance, but his shot went wide of the right post.
Yves Bissouma had a great chance, but he was slow to pass the ball.
Mali continues to press forward to increase its lead.
The first half ends with Mali's 1-0 partial victory over Eswatini.
Mali's number 12, Mohamed Camara, missed an opportunity where he could have advanced further into the six-yard box.
Mali missed the second goal from a low cross by number 21, Salim Diakite, where number 9, Mamadou Doumbia, could not reach the ball.
Adama Malouda Traoré misses another chance for Mali, as his shot goes over the goal.
Mali tries to advance a lot on the flanks, but lacks the final touch.
First change for Mali: Out: Djenepo, In: Camara.
Heavy collision between number 19, Mali Moussa Djenepo, and number 12, Mpendulo Tfomo, from Eswatini.
Eswatini takes the first shot, but it goes wide of Mali's goal.
Gooooool for Mali: Eswatini's poor kick-off, the defender is robbed of the ball and the number 10, Yves Bissouma, takes advantage to make it 1-0.
Pre-Game Insights: The team led by fellow Swazi Dominic Kunene will be looking for their first ever qualification for the African Cup of Nations.
Mali is a major powerhouse in youth football both in Africa and around the world, having never qualified for any World Cup as a senior national team in its history.
Post-Match Reflections: Mali gets a good away win on the other hand Eswatini stays at the bottom of the table.
